Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop them onto a
large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{1}(drizzle), season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}, then sprinkle over half the @ground turmeric{1}.

Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

== Saag Paneer ==

Meanwhile, cut the @paneer{226%g} into 2cm chunks. Halve the
@baby plum tomatoes{125%g}.

Heat the @olive oil{1}(see pantry for amount) in a large #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the paneer to the frying pan. Fry until golden all over,
~{5-8%minutes}. Turn regularly to brown them evenly.

Stir the @ginger puree{7.5%g}, @North Indian style spice mix{2} and remaining
turmeric into the frying pan until the paneer is well coated.

Add the tomatoes and cook for ~{30%seconds}, then stir in the
@vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{100%ml}.

Bring to the boil, stirring to combine, then lower the heat to a simmer.

Stir the @baby spinach{100%g} in a handful at a time until wilted and piping
hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir through the @mango chutney{40%g}, drizzle over the
@Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}, then season to taste with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

== To Serve ==

When everything is ready, share the turmeric potatoes between your
#bowls{} and top with the saag paneer.

Enjoy!